observations.recommendation:
We recommended the following:

The Municipal Mayor direct the Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of all PPE at least once a year, submit the RPCPPE that includes all properties and coordinate closely with the Municipal Accountant for the reconciliation of results of the RPCPPE with the accounting records;
The Municipal Accountant maintain PPELCs for all PPEs;
The General Services Officer – Designate create PCs per category of PPE indicating therein the relevant information for proper monitoring; and
The Municipality undertake the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances of government agencies as prescribed in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
Ensure that the MPDC closely coordinate with the Local Chief Executive and other members of the Municipal Planning and Development Council for the implementation of priority projects under the Municipality’s Local Development Plan to see to it that these plans are carried out on a timely manner and its purpose be achieved for the benefit of its constituents;
Maximize the utilization of the 20% Development Fund for socio-economic developments;
Prepare a monthly utilization report detailing the status and timeframe of each project/program to facilitate in the monitoring of such fund; and
Maintain a subsidiary schedule of the specific projects to be implemented under each line item of the PPAs in the AIP.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

Strictly comply with the requirements in the grant and liquidation of cash advances in accordance with existing rules and regulations;

Refrain from granting additional cash advances to officers and employees with existing unliquidated cash advance;

Require the immediate liquidation of cash advances for local travel within (30) days after the return of the official/employee to his official station, otherwise, exercise the remedy of withholding of salary of the concerned officers/employees when they fail to liquidate their cash advances after receiving demand letters as provided under COA Circular No. 97-002;

For retired officials/employees with unliquidated cash advances, deduction be made from their unpaid claims/benefits or exhaustive efforts be undertaken to properly inform them of their outstanding obligations with the Municipal Government; and

Ensure that no clearance would be issued to transferring/retiring officials and employees unless their outstanding cash advances are first settled.

We reiterated our previous recommendations that Management:

Conduct their procurement early to be able to have sufficient time to address problems encountered during the procurement process;

Thoroughly evaluate the proposed projects and see to it that all factors are considered prior to approval in order to minimize delays and reprogramming;

Carefully plan their projects to ensure that what is planned and targeted are achievable and/or implementable during the calendar year; and

Strictly monitor the implementation of projects and see to it that projects are completed within the targeted completion date.

