We recommended the following:

The Municipal Accountant regularly prepare bank reconciliation statements for all bank accounts and submit promptly to the Office of the Auditor together with other documents as prescribed by COA Circular No. 96-011 dated October 2, 1996;

The Municipal Accountant draw a Journal Entry Voucher to book up reconciling items not taken up in the books;

The Municipal Treasurer record all transactions in her cashbooks daily;

Proper coordination between the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer be conducted to ensure the prompt recording of reconciling items; and

Outstanding checks that has become stale should not be treated as deductions from bank balance in the bank reconciliation statement but a JEV should be drawn to return them to the book balance.

We recommended that the:

Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Assessor to prepare and submit a schedule bearing the names of landowners with areas and assessed value of the lands they own to the Municipal Treasurer to be used as basis for updating the Real Property Tax Account Register /Taxpayers’ Index Cards;

Municipal Treasurer update her Real Property Tax Account Register/Taxpayers’ Index Cards and submit a certified list of taxpayers with the corresponding amounts to the Municipal Accountant at the beginning of the calendar year.  The total amount in the certified list should reconcile with the total amount per schedule furnished by the Municipal Assessor; 

Municipal Accountant prepare a Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to set up the receivable account based on the duly certified list at the beginning of the year and ensure the proper recording of collections in the corresponding subsidiary ledger;

Municipal Assessor furnish the Accounting Office a copy of his report submitted to the Municipal Treasurer on new real properties subject to tax with the corresponding amount of receivables; and

Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant reconcile their account balances at year end.

We recommended that:

The Local Chief Executive create a Property Disposal Committee to undertake inspection and prepare an Inventory and Inspection Report on Unserviceable Properties (IIRUP) and Waste Materials Report (WMR);

The Local Chief Executive request inspection and valuation of the aforementioned properties to the COA Technical Audit Specialists (TAS);

Based on the COA TAS recommendations, the agency undertake the disposal of properties; and

The Municipal Accountant draw a JEV to drop the unserviceable properties from the books of accounts.

